A common problem that you may face in jQuery is that e.stopPropagation() is not working on live events.

In the following example we have a link inside a paragraph. Without propagation check , when ever we click on the link, the click of the p element will be triggered too. With $(e.target).is('a') we can check if the event was triggered by an element of type &lt;a&gt;. If it did, it just "returns" which means that the function will not be executed from that point on.
<pre lang="html4strict" line="1">
<p>
    <a href="#" class="myLink">click me</a>
    <br/>
    You can also click here
</p>;
</pre>

<pre lang="javascript" line="1">
$('a').live('click',function(e){
    alert('a is clicked'); 
});

$('p').live('click', function(e) {
    if ( $(e.target).is('a') ) {return; }
    alert('p is clicked');
});
</pre>

I wanted to share with you a way to get the Twitter users and hashtags from any tweet using regular expressions in PHP and in Javascript.

<strong>PHP</strong>
<pre lang="php">$tweet = 'The @AustralianOpen final is set! @andy_murray will face #Djokovic after beating #Ferrer http://72lions.com';
//Links
$tweet = preg_replace('/http([s]?)://([^ )$]*)/','<a rel="nofollow" href="http$1://$2">http$1://$2</a>',$tweet);
//Users
$tweet = preg_replace('/(^|s)@(w+)/','1@<a href="http://www.twitter.com/2">2</a>', $tweet);
//Hashtags
$tweet = preg_replace('/(^|s)#(w+)/', '1#<a href="http://twitter.com/search/%232">2</a>', $tweet);
//Displaying the outcome
echo $tweet;</pre>
<strong>Javascript</strong>
<pre lang="javascript">var tweet = 'The @AustralianOpen final is set! @andy_murray will face #Djokovic after beating #Ferrer http://72lions.com';
//Links
tweet = tweet.replace(/http([s]?)://([^ )$]*)/g,"<a rel='nofollow' href='http$1://$2'>http$1://$2</a>");
//Users
tweet = tweet.replace(/(^|s)@(w+)/g, "$1@<a href='http://www.twitter.com/$2'>$2</a>");
//Mentions
tweet = tweet.replace(/(^|s)#(w+)/g, "$1#<a href='http://twitter.com/search/%23$2'>$2</a>");
document.write(tweet);</pre>

It is well known that IE6 and some other old browsers don't support the min-height attribute. The following example will make elements with the "selector" class to have a min-height of 300px in older browsers.

<pre lang="css">.selector {
   min-height:300px;
   height:auto !important;
   height:300px;
}</pre>

On this tutorial I am going to demonstrate how we can use the Communication API for Cross Document Messaging.

Until now, if you wanted to communicate between iframes, tabs or windows you would have to do it with direct scripting. A script running in one page would try to change another document, but that might not be allowed due to security restrictions. With the Communication API and the postMessage we now have asynchronous message passing between Javascript contexts.

As shown in the following example, it is very simple to send a message with the postMessage API.
<pre lang="javascript">somewindow.postMessage('This is a message', 'http://example.com');</pre>
To receive messages you have to listen for the 'message' event in the target pages. When a message arrives you get an object that contains information about the message. You can check the origin to see if it comes from a domain that you are interested in receiving messages, and then you can act accordingly. Listening for a message is really simple an it is shown in the next example.
<pre lang="javascript">window.addEventListener('message', messageHandler, true);

function messageHandler(e) {
	//Check the origin of the message
	switch(e.origin) {
	//if it is the domain that we are listening from
		case "http://example.com":
			//Do something with the e.data
			alert(e.data);
			break;
		default:
			//Do nothing if the domain is not the one we are listening from
	}
}</pre>
Since the e.data is a string, we can send a single text or even a JSON object.

<h3>ORIGIN SECURITY</h3>

Cross Origin Communication identifies the sender by origin. This allows the receiver to ignore messages from domains that it doesn't trust. Origins are made up of a scheme, a host and a port. Keep in mind that the path is not included in the origin. So a page at http://example.com/page1.html has the same origin with a page at http://example.com/page2.html because only the path is changed. But http://example.com and https://example.com have a different origin because the scheme is different (http vs. https).

<h3>BE CAREFUL WITH EXTERNAL INPUT</h3>

You should avoid evaluating the e.data as markup. For example the following example is dangerous:
<pre lang="javascript">//e.data is evaluated as markup
el.innerHTML = e.data;</pre>
That's why a better approach is the following:
<pre lang="javascript">//e.data isn't evaluated as markup
el.textContent = e.data;</pre>

<h3>CHECKING FOR BROWSER SUPPORT</h3>

<pre lang="javascript">if(typeof window.postMessage === "undefined"){
	alert('Your browser doesn't support postMessage');
} else {
	//Do something
}</pre>

<h3>SENDING MESSAGES</h3>

The postMessage function get two arguments. The first one is the message and the second one is the intended target
<pre lang="javascript">window.postMessage('Hello world...', 'http://example.com');</pre>
If you want to communicate with an iframe then the code above would change to something like that:
<pre lang="javascript">document.getElementsByTagName('iframe')[0].contentWindow.postMessage('Hello world...', 'http://example.com');</pre>
<h3>LISTENING FOR MESSAGES</h3>

You can receive messages by listening for the message event on the recipient's window object. Then by checking the origin you can decide what to do with the message
<pre lang="javascript">/**
* Handles the messave event
*/
function messageHandler(e) {

	//Check the origin of the message
	switch(e.origin) {
	//if it is the domain that we are listening from
		case "http://localhost":
			//Do something with e.data
                        break;
                default:
			//Do nothing if the domain is not the one we are listening from
	}
}

//Bind events
window.addEventListener('message', messageHandler, true);</pre>
